## Why This Is Asked
This question tests the ability to implement a memory-bounded streaming window per key with online aggregation using only the standard library.

## Key Concepts
- Streaming data ingestion from NDJSON
- Per-key sliding window algorithm
- Incremental average computation
- Memory-bounded state management
- Type validation

## Code Example
```javascript
import { Readable } from 'stream';

class SlidingWindowProcessor {
  constructor(windowSeconds = 60) {
    this.windowSeconds = windowSeconds;
    this.sensors = new Map();
  }

  process(lines, sink) {
    for (const line of lines) {
      const record = JSON.parse(line);
      const { ts, sensor, val } = record;

      if (typeof ts !== 'number' || typeof sensor !== 'string' || typeof val !== 'number') {
        throw new Error('Invalid types');
      }

      if (!this.sensors.has(sensor)) {
        this.sensors.set(sensor, { buffer: [], sum: 0 });
      }

      const sensorState = this.sensors.get(sensor);
      sensorState.buffer.push({ ts, val });
      sensorState.sum += val;

      while (sensorState.buffer.length && sensorState.buffer[0].ts < ts - this.windowSeconds) {
        sensorState.sum -= sensorState.buffer.shift().val;
      }

      const avg = sensorState.sum / sensorState.buffer.length;
      sink({ sensor, average: avg });
    }
  }
}

// Test harness
const testLines = [
  JSON.stringify({ ts: 1000, sensor: 's1', val: 10 }),
  JSON.stringify({ ts: 1005, sensor: 's1', val: 20 }),
  JSON.stringify({ ts: 1010, sensor: 's1', val: 30 }),
  JSON.stringify({ ts: 1070, sensor: 's1', val: 100 }),
];

const processor = new SlidingWindowProcessor(60);
const results = [];
processor.process(testLines, (r) => results.push(r));
console.log(results);
// Output: [{ sensor: 's1', average: 10 }, { sensor: 's1', average: 15 }, { sensor: 's1', average: 20 }, { sensor: 's1', average: 50 }]
```

## Why This Is Asked

Tests practical Python streaming, lightweight validation without heavy libs, and per-line memory safety.

## Key Concepts

